Detailed Findings

#YDU0NR TLS Detection Vulnerability

Description
The "TLS Detection" vulnerability occurs when a web server or API is improperly configured, allowing attackers to detect the presence or absence of Transport Layer Security (TLS). This can happen due to insecure configurations, such as exposing the protocol version or weak ciphers used during the handshake. Detecting the version of TLS or the cipher suite allows attackers to exploit known vulnerabilities in outdated or weak implementations, increasing the risk of man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks, protocol downgrade attacks, and other forms of exploitation.
Endpoint Risk
app.chaindesk.ai:443 Medium
Security Risk
TLS Detection vulnerabilities can have a significant impact on the security of an API or web service. Attackers can identify weak or outdated TLS configurations and exploit them to intercept or modify sensitive data during transmission. This could lead to confidentiality breaches, data tampering, and loss of integrity. Furthermore, weak TLS configurations may expose the system to protocol downgrade attacks, where an attacker forces the system to use a less secure version of TLS, making it easier to compromise.
Mitigation
To mitigate TLS Detection vulnerabilities, ensure that all servers and APIs are configured to use secure and modern versions of TLS, such as TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3. Disable outdated protocols, such as SSL or early versions of TLS, and ensure that only strong cipher suites are used during the handshake process. Regularly audit the TLS configuration and use automated tools to identify weak or insecure configurations. Implement strict certificate validation and enable forward secrecy to further strengthen the security of the communication channels.
Steps To Reproduce
NOTE : Make sure you have OpenSSL installed on your system

Command : openssl s_client -connect app.chaindesk.ai:443
Output
TLS - 1.0
